[Compared to veterinary medicine, human medicine displays a lack of known
teratogenic infections and associated congenital problems. We vets have it
easy as we routinely know when livestock are served and got pregnant,
usually in large numbers, sometimes similtaneously, housed/grazed together
(thereby sharing incidental infections quite apart from experimental
exposures), and with detailed genetic knowledge of the dams and sire(s).
For those interested in such human problems the methodology behind this and
related human studies given in the same surveillance report are worth
reading. There must be more conditions like this in human medicine,
waiting to be described. Martin Hugh-Jones, ProMED-AHEAD moderator (pro
tem) ......................................mhj/es
